 and Darwin's Nightmare, the book also draws on lesser-known film examples, and is one of the first to bring film studies understandings to new media such as YouTube. The result is a study that melds film studies and animal studies to explore how documentary films render both humans and animals, and to what political ends.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aAnimals in motion pictures. 0aDocumentary filmsxHistory and criticism. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Film Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Animal Rights. 4aScience, Mathematics, and Technology : Animal Behavior. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2016z978311149098440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846250940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438462509423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438462509/original  a978-3-11-149098-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles